The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) advise against all but essential travel to San Marino, due to an ongoing outbreak of coronavirus (Covid-19) and in line with various controls and restrictions imposed by the Sammarinese authorities on 8 March and in conjunction with our Travel Advice for Italy
British nationals remain able to depart San Marino without restriction with a valid passport and onward ticket. Airports remain open throughout Italy. The Italian authorities have advised that tourists already on holiday should end their travel, unless it is necessary, to return to the place where they live.
Additional restrictions include the suspension of all public gatherings including sporting events and religious ceremonies. Schools and higher education institutions are currently closed. You can find more information on the emergency measures in place on the San Marino Ministry of Foreign Affairs website (in Italian and English).
If you believe you have symptoms, please do not go directly to a hospital or health care facility. Instead, please call San Marino’s coronavirus emergency number 0549 994001 (from 0800 – 1800) or 0549 888888 (from 1800 – 0800). For further information see Health
Although there’s no recent history of terrorism in San Marino, attacks can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
The European Health Insurance Card (EHIC) is not valid in San Marino.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
Around 6,000 British nationals visit San Marino every year. Most visits are trouble-free.
The emergency services numbers in San Marino are: 112/113 (emergency service, gendarmerie), 115 (public safety, fire department, local police), 118 (emergency ambulance and medical services).
Consular support is not available from the British government in San Marino. However, the British Embassy in Rome, Italy can provide consular support to British nationals.
